close_symbols: condvar internal object definition / OS condvar object table
explanation:
For a MISRA <string.h> bounds-safety check you must inspect not only the target function but all functions and types it calls (directly and transitively) that might invoke standard string functions or operate on buffers whose sizes matter. Each listed symbol is required for the following reasons:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Direct callee in the target function; its implementation must be inspected for any use of string.h functions or operations on name/buffer fields.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Transitive callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById per the static call graph; any of these may use string functions or manipulate buffers/indices that could cause out-of-bounds accesses.
- OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl: Direct callee invoked when OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds; its implementation must be checked for string.h usage (e.g., copying or comparing object names) and for correct buffer bounds handling.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Transitive callee used by OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl; may access object tables/records and thus its use of pointers/buffer accesses must be examined.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test/stub harness functions appear in the static call graph for the target; builds or test instrumentation may route calls through these stubs — they can contain string handling (for logging, context, or stub data) so include them to ensure no hidden string.h violations are introduced by test wrappers.
- OS_object_token_t, osal_id_t, int32: Type definitions used by the target and called functions; necessary to determine pointer/structure layouts and size/length of members involved in any string operations.
- OS_SUCCESS, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: Constants/macros used by the target and its callees; their values can affect control flow (e.g., which code paths are executed) and thus which string operations are reachable.
- condvar internal object definition / OS condvar object table: The internal condvar object structure and the global object table(s) accessed by OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl / OS_ObjectIndexFromToken must be inspected to see fields (names, buffers) that could be the target of string.h calls and to verify sizes and indexing to rule out out-of-bounds accesses.

In short: to determine if OS_CondVarUnlock (or its callees/transitive callees) violate the MISRA string-bounds rule you must have the source/prototypes/definitions for the listed functions, the unit-test stub helpers (if present in your build), and the relevant types and object-table/record definitions so you can trace any use of memcpy/strcpy/strlen/etc. and verify buffer sizes and indexing.
